05663nam a22009255i 9783110750041DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107500417 a10.1515/97831107500412doi  a(DE-B1597)582714  a(OCoLC)1266228633  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aBD311b.O58 2021 7aPHI0390002bisacsh04a11122300aOntological Commitment Revisited /ced. by Jesús Padilla Gálvez. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (V, 159 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAporia ,x2197-862X ;v1300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tOntological Commitment: An Introduction -- tMeinong’s Objectives -- tMetaphysical Aspects of Agency -- tRepresentation as Ontological Problem -- tOntological Commitment and State of Affairs -- t“I know” Language-games in Wittgenstein’s Late Philosophy -- tAgainst Propositional Substantivism -- tWittgenstein’s Nachlass, a Case for Practical Ontology? -- tParadox in Ontology: Black Holes, Cosmology, Wittgenstein versus Stephen Hawking’s Claim that Philosophy is Dead -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex of Names -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOntological commitment implies that each theory is supposed to specify the type of entities that form its components. Representatives of a theory share an ontological commitment in relation to the objects they refer to. There are theories that admit the existence of universals while others do not. As there are different ways of speaking about universals it is necessary to decide what a universal term corresponds to. It is essential to have a criterion that enables us to decide which kinds of objects are allowed as references for the terms used. In this volume two different approaches are discussed: first, in cases where only extensional languages are accepted; second, when intensional elements are required to determine the meaning such terms as "Sachverhalt", intentional statements or representations. The ontological commitment associated with extensional theories exclusively admits the existence of physical objects, whereas intensional theses additionally include universal and abstract entities. The study of ontological commitment enables us to measure the ontological economy of theories. This serves as a basis for the choice of theory. The authors of this volume discuss relevant issues of both models and provide new solutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aOntology. 4aExistenz. 4aOntologie. 4aUrteilskraft. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Analytic.2bisacsh  aOntology.  aexistence.  alanguages.  aontological commitment.  atruth-conditions.1 aGaffal, Margit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía-Carpintero, Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibson, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarques, António, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNida-Rümelin, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPadilla Gálvez, Jesús, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPadilla Gálvez, Jesús, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSimons, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE